VALUES ('b9c0d1e2-f3a4-4b5c-6d7e-8f9a0b1c2d3e', 'jack-rose', 'i9j0k1l2m3n4o5p6q7r8s9t0u1v2w3x4y5z6a7b8', '{"en":"Jack Rose"}'::jsonb, 'famous', NULL, '{"classic","vintage","famous","applejack","citrus","prohibition-era"}', '{"en":"A Prohibition-era classic showcasing American apple brandy. The Jack Rose combines applejack with citrus and grenadine for a tart, fruity cocktail with a beautiful pink hue. Simple yet sophisticated, it''s a forgotten gem from the golden age of cocktails."}'::jsonb, '{"created_year":"1905","origin":{"city":"New York City / New Jersey","bar":"Unknown","country":"USA"},"creator":{"name":"Unknown (possibly Frank J. May)","profession":"bartender"},"story":{"en":"The Jack Rose emerged around 1905 and became one of the most popular cocktails of the pre-Prohibition and Prohibition eras. Its origin is disputed - some attribute it to bartender Frank J. May in New Jersey, while others claim it was created in New York. The drink gained fame when it was mentioned in Ernest Hemingway''s \"The Sun Also Rises\" and John Steinbeck''s works. During Prohibition, its pink color and fruity flavor helped mask the harsh taste of bootleg spirits. The cocktail showcases applejack, America''s oldest spirit, which was easier to produce during Prohibition than imported liquors. After Prohibition, the Jack Rose faded into obscurity but has been revived by modern craft bartenders."},"named_after":{"en":"The name''s origin is debated: possibly named after the pink Jacquemot rose, notorious gambler \"Bald Jack\" Rose, or applejack combined with rose (pink color)."}}'::jsonb, '{"profile":["tart","fruity","apple"],"description":{"en":"Tart, fruity, and refreshing. The Jack Rose balances the rich apple character of applejack with bright lemon acidity and the pomegranate sweetness of grenadine. The result is a sophisticated sour with depth from the aged apple brandy."},"first_impression":{"en":"Bright citrus and pomegranate followed by rich apple notes"},"finish":{"en":"Clean, tart finish with lingering apple and subtle oak notes from the brandy"},"balance":{"en":"Well-balanced between tart citrus and sweet grenadine, with apple brandy providing depth"}}'::jsonb, '{"best_time":["evening","late_afternoon"],"occasions":["aperitivo","sophisticated","date_night","social"],"seasons":["autumn","spring"],"food_pairings":{"en":"Pairs well with pork dishes, roasted poultry, apple-based desserts, and sharp cheeses. Also excellent with autumn harvest fare and charcuterie boards."},"ideal_for":{"en":"Perfect for those who appreciate classic sours and American spirits. Ideal for cocktail historians and anyone looking to explore Prohibition-era drinks. A great choice for autumn gatherings."}}'::jsonb, '[{"ingredient_id":"ING_APPLEJACK","quantity":{"amount":45,"unit":"ml"},"display_name":"Applejack or Calvados","notes":null},{"ingredient_id":"ING_LEMON_JUICE","quantity":{"amount":22.5,"unit":"ml"},"display_name":"Fresh lemon juice","notes":null},{"ingredient_id":"ING_GRENADINE","quantity":{"amount":15,"unit":"ml"},"display_name":"Grenadine","notes":null}]'::jsonb, 'shake', '{"en":"Pour all ingredients into a cocktail shaker filled with ice. Shake vigorously until well-chilled. Strain into a chilled cocktail glass. No garnish needed."}'::jsonb, 'Cocktail glass (Coupe)', '{"en":"None"}'::jsonb, 'none', 'up', '{"ING_APPLEJACK"}', '{"tart","fruity","apple"}', 20, 150, 'easy', 60, '{}', '{"alcohol"}', '{"vegetarian","vegan","pescatarian","gluten_free","nut_free","dairy_free"}', 0, '{"vegetarian","vegan","gluten-free"}', '{"autumn","spring"}', '{"aperitivo","sophisticated","date_night","social"}', false, false, '{"applejack-rabbit","pink-lady"}', 'Use real grenadine (pomegranate syrup), not artificial red syrup. Applejack is traditional, but Calvados makes an excellent substitute. Shake hard to properly chill and dilute. The ratio is typically 2:1:0.5 (applejack:lemon:grenadine).', 'mid', 50, 'https://www.diffordsguide.com/cocktails/recipe/1169/jack-rose', 'Classic recipe from the early 1900s, documented in various cocktail books.', 1)
